Toona ciliata

   [10458.jpg]
   Authority M.J. Roem
   Family Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Sapindales:Meliaceae
   Synonyms Toona australis (F. Muell.) Harms, Toona ciliata ssp. ciliata
   var. australis (F. Muell.) Bahadur, Toona ciliata var. australis (F.
   Muell.) C. DC., Toona microcarpa (C.DC.) Harms, Toona ternatensis
   (Miq.) Bahadur., Cedrela toona var. australis (F. Muell.) C. DC.,
   Cedrela toona Roxb. ex Rottler and Willd.
   Common names mahanim, tun, tuni, taung-tama, taw thamgo, thit kador,
   Australian red cedar, Burma cedar, Indian cedar, moulmein cedar,
   Queensland red cedar, red cedar, toon, danupra, cedre rouge, lim,
   kukoru, malapoga, suren kapar, suren mal, chomcha, mai-yom-horm,
   ranggoh, surian limpaga, cedro, mala-vembu, santhana-vembu,
   thevetharem, yom-hom, l[as]t kh[es]t
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 10458

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION: A tall deciduous or almost evergreen tree with a
   spreading crown. The tree can reach a height of 30-35 m. GROWING
   PERIOD: Perennial. COMMON NAMES: Toona, Toon, Myanmar ceder, Red Cedar,
   Moulmein cedar, Poma, Tun, Mandurike, Ahil, Kuruk, Mahalimbu, Drawi,
   Nandivriksha, Santhana-vembu, Nandichettu. FURTHER INF: Scientific
   synonym: Cedrela toona. It can be found in the sub-Himalayan tract and
   valleys, in India, Bangladesh and Myanmar at elevations between sea
   level and 1500 m. The latitudinal range of natural occurrence is
   15-30Â°N. It occurs naturally on moist sites such as ravines, stream
   banks and swamps, but it tended and watered in youth it is capable of
   growing in comparatively dry sites. Young trees require shade, while
   mature trees are moderate light demanders. The tree is termite
   resistant, but sesitive to fire. In India, adapted to a relative
   humidity in July from 70-90% and in January from 45-80%. Annual wood
   production potential is 7-20 m3/ha.

   Sources
